Recommended for the crop requires 4 - 6 irrigations depending on the soil type and rainfall. Wheat crop requires minimum of 5 irrigations at the following critical stages.
I – Immediately after sowing
II – Crown root initiation: 15-20 DAS 
III- Active tillering stage: 35-40 DAS
IV- Flowering stage: 50-55 DAS
V- Grain filling stage: 70-75 DAS
Crown root initiation and flowering are the most critical stages. Water stagnation should be voided at the time of germination.

Recommended  for The crop requires 4 - 6 irrigations depending on the soil type and rainfall. Wheat crop requires minimum of 5 irrigations at the following critical stages.
I – Immediately after sowing
II – Crown root intiation : 15-20 DAS 
III- Active tillering stage : 35-40 DAS
IV- Flowering stage : 50-55 DAS
V- Grain filling stage : 70-75 DAS
Crown root initiation and flowering are the most critical stages. Water stagnation should be voided at the time of germination.

Recommended for the crop requires 4 - 6 irrigations depending on the soil type and rainfall. Wheat crop requires minimum of 5 irrigations at the following critical stages.
I – Immediately after sowing
II – Crown root intiation : 15-20 DAS 
III- Active tillering stage : 35-40 DAS
IV- Flowering stage : 50-55 DAS
V- Grain filling stage : 70-75 DAS
Crown root initiation and flowering are the most critical stages. Water stagnation should be voided at the time of germination.

Recommended for The crop requires 4 - 6 irrigations depending on the soil type and rainfall. Wheat crop requires minimum of 5 irrigations at the following critical stages.
I – Immediately after sowing,
II – Crown root intiation : 15-20 DAS 
III- Active tillering stage : 35-40 DAS
IV- Flowering stage : 50-55 DAS
V- Grain filling stage : 70-75 DAS
Crown root initiation and flowering are the most critical stages. Water stagnation should be voided at the time of germination.

KCCAns:
Rattanidhi sampling aggregation method-

1- Visit the field in which the sampling is to be done by jig-jig and mark it at 10-15 places so that all parts of the farm can be included in it.

2- Remove debris, debris etc. from the upper surface on the selected places.

3- 15 cm at all these places (6-9 inch) dig deeper V shaped cord. Cleansing the pot from the top of the scalp, up to 2 cm from the top. Remove the thick soil from the bottom and put it in a clean bucket or tray.

4- Mix the collected clay well with the hands and put on clean clothes and make a round pile. Remove the clay from the finger to the four equal parts and remove the soil separately. Now mix the remaining two parts again and make the rounds. Repeat this procedure till almost half of the remains are left in the soil. This representative will be sample.

5- Keep the dry soil sample in a clean plastic bag and put it in a garment bag. An information sheet along with the sample on which all the information is written, put it in a plastic bag and outside the clothes bag.

6- Now send these prepared samples to the soil testing laboratory.

KCCAns: Satpura plant is shrubbery, thorny vine. Its branches are thin The leaves are like needles, which are 1.5-2.5 cm long. Its forks are crooked and 6-8 cm long. Its branches are spread all around. Its flowers appear on white or pinkish aromatic, tiny, multiple stalks, which grow in February and March. Fruits grow bigger in April. Fruits are 1-2 seeds, similar to peas. Its seeds are black on ripening. Its roots are grown in 20-30 cm long, 1-2 cm thick and in flakes. The number of roots is up to 60-100 in every vine. These aromatic yellowish yellowish flavored flavors seem to be sweet and bitter. The fleshy roots are eaten by the tribals on the whole cook. It is also used on drying. These white roots are used for medical work. The dry root market is sold in the name of Satavar. In which glucose chemistry is found prominently in Satavirin-1 and Satavarin-4. This chemical is the source of its medicinal properties.

KCCAns:
1. Amrapali (Dushahari - Sapphire): This is a hybrid variety whose plants are dwarves and this type is suitable for intensive gardening. Its fruits are small in size, but they are rewarded annually. This is a late ripening product where fruits are cooked at the end of June. In intensive horticulture, it yields 200-250 quintals / hectare.

2. Mallika (Sapphire - Doshera): This is a hybrid variety whose fruits are very large (average weight is 500 grams). The color of the fruit is pink-yellow, kernels are sweet, sweet and tasty. This is a regular type of fruit. This type of storage capacity is high; this type is suitable for food and processing. On average, a complete grown tree receives 150-200 kg of fruit.

3. Dusheshi: The origin of this variety is Lucknow and it is a popular variety of North India's main and tastes. This is a kind of ripening from mid-June to July. The tree is spreading medium height and the top is circular. Fruits, medium size weights are 125-250 grams, color yellow, shiny thin, fiber-free pulp and kernels are small. Fruits are good storage capacity.

4. Lame: It originated in the village, near Banaras. This variety gives fruit by the end of May to July. The tree is the spreading nature and the top is circular. The fruit is medium-sized oval, color green, fiber-free pulp and small kernels. Fruit storage capacity is low. Its average production is 150-200 kg. Till per tree.

5. Sunderja: This is a medium-sized type of breed, whose origin is Rewa. The fruit is medium size, weighing 200-250 grams, skew, oval, color is yellow, fragrant and delicious. It is highly susceptible to bandha disease (mango malformations).

6. Garazia: It is the main type of Betul. The fruit is larger than medium, rectangular, slightly flat, base spherical, yellow-green on color, white spots on the skin, shiny medium to thick, pulp is juicy and very sweet. There is an aroma like pineapple and it is called carrarias due to the similarity of pulp carrots. The cook time is from mid-May to last June.

7. Dheer: It is a juicy variety of Bhopal, whose fruit is medium size, oblique, oval, top rounded chaya, yellow green color is thick, the pulp is juicy, sweet, light yellow fibers without color. Due to sugars mixed with curd, it is called dhir.

8. Bombaygreen: This is a quick cooked variety, whose fruits are cooked in the third week of May. This type of tree is more branched and the leaves are thin. Fruits are medium-sized, greenish on ripening, high pulp in fruit and good taste and sweetness.
9. Alfanzo: This is the popular variety of Ratnagiri (Maharashtra). Fruit size medium, (weight 250g), pulp is soft, fiber-free, color orange, flavor is sour sweet. There is deformity called spongy tissue. Its storage capacity is good and suitable for export.

KCCAns:
1- Visit the field in which sampling is to be done by jig-jig and mark it at 10-15 places so that all parts of the farm can be included in it.

2- Remove debris, debris etc. from the upper surface on the selected places.

3- 15 cm at all these places (6-9 inch) dig deeper V shaped cord. Cleansing the pot from the top of the scalp, up to 2 cm from the top. Remove the thick soil from the bottom and put it in a clean bucket or tray.

4- Mix the collected clay well with hand and make a round pile by putting it on clean clothes. Remove the clay from finger to four equal parts and remove the soil separately. Now mix the remaining two parts again and make the rounds. Repeat this procedure until almost half of the remains are left in the soil. This representative will be sample.

5- Keep the dry soil sample in a clean plastic bag and put it in a garment bag. Insert a notice sheet with a sample on which all the information is written, inside a plastic bag and outside a garment bag.

6- Now send these prepared samples to the soil testing laboratory.
